  "text": "Quick Links Installed Apps in Windows 11 is an updated version of Apps \u0026 Features in Windows 10 and the old Programs and Features tool in the Control Panel. There are many ways to open this tool, but these are the easiest. The WinX menu, also known as the power user menu, is a quick and easy way to access system tools and settings in Windows 11. Microsoft first introduced it in Windows 8, and it has remained a handy feature ever since. To open the Installed Apps tool using the WinX menu, follow these steps: Right-click the Start button or hit Windows + X on your keyboard. From the menu that pops up, click Installed apps. The Installed Apps tool will open, showing you all the apps installed on your computer. 2 Use Windows Search You can use Windows Search like a personal assistant to help you find almost anything on your computer. This means you can use it to quickly open the Installed Apps tool by following these steps: Click the search icon or press Win + S on your keyboard. Type installed apps into the search box and click Open on the search results. 3 Use the Run Command The Run command on Windows allows you to access system tools and settings quickly by typing in the appropriate commands. To access the Installed Apps tool using the Run command, follow these steps: Press Win + R on your keyboard to open the Run window. Type ms-settings:appsfeatures in the box and hit Enter. The Settings app in Windows 11 allows you to customize and manage almost everything on your computer. Thereâ€™s even a section just for handling your installed apps. To open installed apps through the Settings menu, do the following: Click the Start menu and select Settings (look for the gear icon). In Settings, click Apps, then Installed apps. This will open a list of all the apps you have installed on your computer so you can manage or uninstall them. These are some of the quickest ways to open the Installed Apps tool on your Windows 11 PC. Next time you want to uninstall or manage an app, try one of these methods.",
